  <slide>
    <title>Optimization problems</title>
    
    <p>
      Standard context: maximize or minimize some quantity, subject to some constraint.
    </p>

    <p>
      For example: find the dimensions of the rectangle of largest area that can fit within a semicircle of radius 4.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>A = LW</m> for a rectangle.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            This is a function of two variables! How do we maximize?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Use the constraint to eliminate a variable...
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    
    <p>
      We might need a picture...
    </p>

    <image source="maxArea.png">
      <shortdescription>A rectangle within a semicircle, but not necessarily of maximal area</shortdescription>
      
    </image>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>A calculus classic: the soda can</title>
    <p>
      A standard soda can holds 355 millilitres (cubic centimetres) of fluid.
    </p>

    <p>
      What should be the dimensions of the can if we want to minimize the amount of material used to manufacture it?
    </p>

    <p pause="yes">
      Note: <q>amount of material</q> is often code for <q>surface area</q>.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Serious business</title>
    <p>
      Here are some fancy terms and functions relevant to people who like money:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>C(x)</m> <mdash/> the cost per unit of producing some item
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>C'(x)</m> <mdash/> the <em>marginal cost</em>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>p(x)</m> <mdash/> the price per unit that can be charged if <m>x</m> units are sold,
            sometimes known as the <em>demand function</em>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>R(x)=xp(x)</m> <mdash/> the <em>revenue function</em>, and <m>R'(x)</m>, the <em>marginal revenue</em>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>P(x)=R(x)-C(x)</m> <mdash/> the <term>profit function</term>, and <m>P'(x)</m>, the <em>marginal profit</em>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>c(x) = C(x)/x</m> denote the <em>average cost</em> of an item. Show that if <m>c(x)</m> is a minimum,
      then the marginal cost equals the average cost.
    </p>
  </slide>

  <slide>
    <title>Something more practical</title>
    <p>
      A box with no lid will be constructed from a 40 cm by 50 cm piece of cardboard,
      by cutting a square from each corner, and then folding up the sides.
    </p>

    <p>
      Determine the size of square that should be cut in order to maximize the volume of the box.
    </p>
  </slide>
